					return "\n## Immediate Safety First\n\nAfter a storm, prioritize safety before anything else.\n\n### Dangers to Watch For\n\n- Downed power lines (stay away, call utility company)\n- Unstable trees or branches\n- Debris and hazards\n- Gas leaks or structural damage\n- Hidden dangers like weakened limbs\n\n## Immediate Actions\n\n### 1. Assess Safety\n\nWalk your property carefully. Look for:\n- Fallen trees or large branches\n- Branches hanging dangerously\n- Power lines down\n- Structural damage\n- Hazardous debris\n\n### 2. Contact Professionals if Needed\n\nCall an arborist immediately if:\n- Power lines are involved\n- Trees are near structures\n- Large trees are unstable\n- You're unsure about safety\n- The damage is extensive\n\n### 3. Document Damage\n\n- Take photos for insurance\n- Write descriptions of damage\n- Note tree locations and size\n- Save receipts for cleanup expenses\n\n### 4. Contact Your Insurance\n\nReport tree damage to your insurance company promptly. Many policies cover tree removal from storms.\n\n## What NOT to Do\n\n- **Don't climb damaged trees** – They're unstable\n- **Don't use chainsaws** if untrained – Very dangerous\n- **Don't touch power lines** – Potentially fatal\n- **Don't ignore warning signs** – Dangers can appear later\n- **Don't delay removal** – Hazardous trees get worse\n\n## Professional Storm Cleanup\n\nAfter severe storms, call a certified arborist for:\n- Hazard tree assessment\n- Safe removal of fallen trees\n- Dangerous branch removal\n- Property damage restoration\n- Debris cleanup\n\n## Insurance Coverage\n\nMany homeowner policies cover:\n- Storm-damaged tree removal\n- Debris cleanup\n- Tree replacement in some cases\n\nCheck your policy. Some require specific documentation.\n\n## Recovery Timeline\n\n**Immediate (24-48 hours):** Safety assessment and emergency removal\n**Short-term (1-2 weeks):** Major debris cleanup\n**Medium-term (1-2 months):** Complete restoration and replanting\n**Long-term:** Landscape recovery and new tree planting\n\n## Prevention for Next Time\n\n- Maintain trees during good weather\n- Remove weak or diseased branches\n- Keep trees healthy and pruned\n- Have emergency numbers ready\n- Consider tree removal before storm season\n\nThe best response to storm damage is quick action and professional help.\n";
